cs.CG, cs.CC, cs.DS, cs.LO, cs.GT. 

The paper deals with geometric problems and their complexity, which suggests cs.CG (Computational Geometry) as the most likely sub-category. The introduction of new complexity classes and the study of their properties also points towards cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The use of tools such as UETR and the focus on graph problems suggest cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as a possible sub-category. The concepts of imprecision, robustness, and extendability mentioned in the abstract may relate to cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) or cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
